post_text:
TOMORROW! Our First Day of School for the 2020/2021 School Year begins tomorrow.

School starts at 8:00 AM on Monday, August 31st for ALL Warrensville Heights Middle and High School Scholars. Elementary scholars first day is also Monday, August 31st. Elementary students attend either an AM or PM session. AM sessions for elementary begin at 9:00 AM and PM sessions for elementary scholars begin at 12:45PM.

The week of August 31st through September 4th is a BLUE remote learning week. This means that MS and HS scholars have certain classes on Monday, Wednesday and Friday and other classes on Tuesday and Thursday. Check out the student schedule here: http://bit.ly/BlueandGoldWHCSD

post_text:
REMINDER: August 31-September 4 is a BLUE Remote Learning Week.

We have had some questions from families about what this means. This is a schedule of classes that impacts our WHHS and WHMS scholars as we worked to fit in an equal amount of learning time across courses. Essentially if a course is held on Monday, Wednesday and Friday during BLUE weeks, it moves to being held on Tuesday and Thursday during GOLD week.

Have more questions? Visit our Reopening 2020 web page here: http://www.warrensville.k12.oh.us/reopening.aspx

Please read this important message from Superintendent Jolly:

Earlier today, the Board of Education gave me authority to declare this Friday, June 19th a District Holiday in order to recognize and honor the importance of Juneteenth. All employees will be compensated as a paid holiday.

Juneteenth commemorates the day when slaves in the last geographic area in America where slavery existed learned of their freedom. This took place on June 19, 1865, in Galveston, Texas, when Union General Gordon Granger read General Order #3, announcing that "all slaves are free" by Proclamation of President Abraham Lincoln. The Emancipation Proclamation was signed by President Abraham Lincoln on September‚Ä¶

post_text:
üößImportant Facility Updateüöß

During the March 4, 2020 Work Session, the Warrensville Heights City School District Board of Education reviewed and discussed options to select a name for the new elementary school building. By a unanimous vote, the board approved the new building name: Warrensville Heights Elementary School (WHES). The name reflects the rich history of our District and the pride of our community.

In the selection of the school name, the Board acknowledged the importance of honoring and celebrating the rich African American heritage in our backyard. The Board, along with Superintendent Jolly, plan to name interior rooms and common spaces after prominent community members.

Please Share: As our school year comes to a conclusion this week, our mobile meal delivery program will also end. Wednesday, May 20th will be our FINAL mobile meal delivery for this school year.

We will launch our Summer Meal Program next Wednesday, May 27th. For the first week ONLY, the drive-thru style meal pickup will be on Wednesday, May 27th and Friday, May 29th from 10:30-11:30am. The drive-thru will take place at Warrensville Heights High School.

For each week thereafter, it will be every Monday and Thursday from 10:30-11:30am. We will provide three days of meals (breakfast and lunch) on each pickup day #TigerPride

post_text:
The Department of Pupil Services will be offering curbside document drop off for District families to complete registration/enrollment for the 20-21 school year.

Please take note of the following details, in particular, families must have an appointment before arrival.

-Parents MUST complete the WHCSD online registration application first.

-Once you have completed the online application, the Department of Pupil Services will contact parents via email and/or phone to schedule curbside appointments to drop off ALL registration documents.

-All visitors MUST wear a mask if they need to enter the Department of Pupil Services.

-Pupil Services will be open on Tuesday, May 5-Thursday, May 7, 2020. Tuesday from 8am-Noon, Wednesday from Noon-4pm and Thursdays from 8am-Noon.

We are looking to expand these days and times so please continue to check back in with our website and social media for further updates #TigerPride

Please Share: The District and School Board are pleased to announce its graduation plans for the Warrensville Heights High School Class of 2020 üéì

Here's the general plan:

‚Ä¢ Beginning May 8th-May 12th we will hold individual graduation ceremonies for each of our seniors.

‚Ä¢ Graduates will come dressed in their cap and gown and hearing their name called, walk the stage to receive their diploma.

‚Ä¢ Graduates will each receive five (5) tickets for friends/family to accompany them to their mini ceremony. Masks must be worn and temperatures taken for admittance--this is to ensure the health and safety of all.

‚Ä¢ We have hired both a photographer and local film company to capture these moments. ‚Ä¶

Please Share: We are proud to announce that WHCSD will join #BeTheLight movement which is gaining momentum throughout the nation, this FRIDAY, April 24th from 8:00-8:20 PM, to honor the seniors of WHHS 2020 and our student athletes whose spring sports season has been cancelled due to the coronavirus crisis.

Players, families, and community members are encouraged to drive by the fields to see the lights, and honk to show support of our scholars.

***Please make sure to drive by only and not gather outside of your vehicles***

We ask our Tri City community who wish to join in from your homes to turn on your porch lights at the same time (8:00-8:20 PM) to show solidarity and unity.

In the darkest times, we all need a little bit of light, a little bit of hope. We would really appreciate if you take a picture of the porch lights or take a family picture by the lights and share with us in the comments or email us at communications@whcsd.org for our social media.
#TigerPride #BeTheLight #ShineYourLight #TigersTogether
text:
Please Share: We are proud to announce that WHCSD will join #BeTheLight movement which is gaining momentum throughout the nation, this FRIDAY, April 24th from 8:00-8:20 PM, to honor the seniors of WHHS 2020 and our student athletes whose spring sports season has been cancelled due to the coronavirus crisis.

Players, families, and community members are encouraged to drive by the fields to see the lights, and honk to show support of our scholars.

***Please make sure to drive by only and not gather outside of your vehicles***

We ask our Tri City community who wish to join in from your homes to turn on your porch lights at the same time (8:00-8:20 PM) to show solidarity and unity.

In the darkest times, we all need a little bit of light, a little bit of hope. We would really appreciate if you take a picture of the porch lights or take a family picture by the lights and share with us in the comments or email us at communications@whcsd.org for our social media.
#TigerPride #BeTheLight #ShineYourLight #TigersTogether

Please visit our website for the full update from Superintendent Jolly: https://bit.ly/3brOTcc

While we still do not have all the answers, we are pleased that this legislation begins to provide us more clarity. Here is a brief highlight of how this impacts our District:

‚Ä¢ All State testing including the Ohio State Tests and End of Course Exams have been suspended.

‚Ä¢ The Third Grade Reading Guarantee is included in this test suspension‚Ä¶

Last week, Warrensville Heights High School held its African-American history month program on Friday, February 28, 2020 with the presentation of the African-American history bowl.

12 teams competed in a tournament style event that focused on African-American history and accomplishments. The culminating activity for the day was held in the afternoon with our keynote speaker of the Honorable Mayor Michael Booker of Highland Hills. The Warrensville Heights High School choir participated with the singing of the African-American National anthem and the championship round between our final two student groups competing to see who will take home the championship award #TigerPride

You may recall that earlier this school year our district received a generous $20k donation from Amazon.com to continue our #STEAM programming.

Thanks to lots of planning and research by our academic coordinators, curriculum team, teachers and STEAM advisory committee we are pleased to reveal the Tiger MILL‚ÄîMobile Innovation Learning Lab! We have created five mobile makerspaces that will be housed at our schools so that staff and scholars can engage in hands-on learning, making, exploring and sharing!

These mobile labs have a variety of equipment specific to the grade levels of our scholars These labs will help prepare our students with the necessary 21st century skills in the fields of science, technology, engineering, arts and math #TigerPride

Congratulations to two WHHS scholars who were the Regional Winners in the State of Ohio Regional Rev. Dr. Martin L. King Jr. Oratorical Contest (Senior Division). The 2020 contest marks the 21st anniversary of the statewide oratorical contest which the state Holiday Commission adopted in 1999.

David Hughley ‚Äî1st place
Autumn Tate- 2nd place

The theme for this year is, ‚ÄúWhere Would We Be? Where Will We Be?‚Äù This theme allows contestants an opportunity to reflect on where we, as a society, would be without Dr. King; as well as how they are part of the solution moving forward.

Both of our winners have advanced to the statewide competition set for April #TigerPride

post_text:
After lots of hard work and discipline, Warrensville Heights High School student Cameron Ray on Dec. 17 became the youngest Warrensville student ever to graduate from Cuyahoga Community College.

Cameron walked across the stage with his associate‚Äôs degree of arts in hand -- well before he is set to graduate high school in 2021.

‚ÄúEveryone is usually pretty surprised when I tell them I‚Äôm only a junior in high school,‚Äù said Cameron, who will go on to study film directing at Cleveland State University next semester.

Cameron began preparing for his early start at Tri-C in middle school through the Ohio College Credit Plus program.

Warrensville‚Äôs dual-credit program and partnership with Tri-C gives students like Cameron a head start to college and career at no cost to parents and families. Ohio College Credit reported that it saved Ohio families more than $148 million in tuition in 2017-18.

Visit our website to read the rest of this amazing story: https://bit.ly/2rNpU25 #TigerPride

Mrs. Busse and her PE class had a special Project Based Learning (PBL) STEAM Winter Fair Project. They created boats üö£üèø‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è out of ordinary objects to see who could win in a race, The Busse Regatta.

Scholars decided their boat style which included a pirate ship, WWII landing craft, a canoe and a raft. All projects included common core standards of math, science, and history as well as culturally responsive teaching. After extensive research on the history of the boats, students designed them and then went to work on the creation.

Mrs. Busse's dad even came in to assist scholars with the design and construction and paid for all the materials as a gift to students #1Team1Vision1Goal #TigerPride
